    <item>
      <title>An Ink-Stained Life</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/an-ink-stained-life/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 09 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/an-ink-stained-life/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;an-ink-stained-life-the-marginalia-of-a-sixteenth-century-cairene-scholar&#34;&gt;An Ink-Stained Life: The Marginalia of a Sixteenth-Century Cairene Scholar&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/images/thabat.png&#34; alt=&#34;A picture of two folios of al-Muẓaffarī&amp;rsquo;s personal register of notes, also called &amp;ldquo;thabat&amp;rdquo;&amp;rsquo;&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;A picture of two folios of al-Muẓaffarī&amp;rsquo;s personal register of notes, also called &amp;ldquo;thabat&amp;rdquo; (Rabat, MS Unknown, fols. 112v-113r)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This dissertation reconstructs the life trajectory, documentary practices, and book consumption of Muḥammad al-Muẓaffarī (d. ca. 950/1543), a minor scholar active in late Mamluk and early Ottoman Cairo, through 665 marginal annotations he wrote in manuscripts now dispersed across libraries worldwide. Al-Muẓaffarī’s notes and his sizeable personal book collection demonstrate that non-elite scholars had substantial access to the intellectual world of late Mamluk Cairo and actively participated in its scholarly community. They sat in mosques, madrasas, shops, and private homes, hearing ḥadīth, copying texts, and writing annotations, generating substantial quantities of documentary material—certificates, reading records, and other marginalia.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
